summary: Raised concerns about tech overreach by Elon Musk and the DOGE administrator accessing sensitive VA systems and veteran data; supported legislation (VA DATA Act of 2025) to block private actors from accessing veterans' information and to tighten controls on data access and retention by special government employees. Also introduced the SBIR Website Improvement Act to modernize SBIR/STTR award data and search capabilities, improving transparency and access to federally funded R&D awards, supporting Phase III commercialization searches, and helping translate innovation into market-ready technologies. Led a bicameral letter with 137 colleagues to the Acting Secretary of Labor expressing serious concerns about reports that Elon Musk and DOGE were granted access to Department of Labor internal systems and worker data, raising questions about conflicts of interest, data access and confidentiality, security and oversight, and personnel protections, and demanding answers by March 7, 2025. Additionally urged modernization of air traffic control technology by requesting $36 million to upgrade the Philadelphia TRACON STARS system, noting the current reliance on commercial telecommunications for critical radar and communications is unsustainable and contributes to outages. Cosponsored the Tobacco TRACE Act to require secure, tamper-resistant tracking codes on tobacco products, leveraging tracking technology to improve monitoring and enforcement across the tobacco supply chain.

Gill answered constituents' questions about DOGE (Dogecoin) and cryptocurrency at town halls, indicating engagement with cryptocurrency and related technology/financial issues. He also announced and celebrated the 2025 Congressional App Challenge winner from TX-26, highlighting student achievement in computer science and fintech (a stock market education app), and expressing support for STEM education and youth innovation in technology. In April 2025 he noted his membership on the newly created DOGE Committee, working on oversight of bureaucrats and programs related to digital assets and federal waste. He has also raised concerns about foreign adversaries influencing university research and academic programs, co-sponsoring the Foreign Influence Transparency and Accountability Act to deter foreign-funded research or gifts from adversarial nations and protect sensitive research, intellectual property, and campus integrity through audits and punitive excise taxes.

Recognized students' information and digital literacy needs and supported investments to address digital literacy as part of strengthening school library programs and modern reading instruction. Cosponsored legislation addressing digital harms and privacy, including the Disrupt Explicit Forged Images and Non-Consensual Edits Act (targeting non-consensual deepfakes/edits) and My Body, My Data Act to protect personal data privacy. Upon being sworn in she pledged to sign a discharge petition for the Taxpayer Data Protection Act, indicating support for congressional action to protect taxpayer data and limit administrative overreach on sensitive personal information.
